Offensive Security Threats and Adaptive Attacks in
Large Language Models: A Literature Review
Deepak Rajamanickkam School Of Computing, Dublin City University, Dublin, Ireland. deepak.rajamanickkam2@mail.dcu.ie
Abstract—State-of-the-art language models like GPT, Gemini, Claude and more have been widely integrated into enterprise software, APIs and smart agents that are available to everyone with internet. However, different types of security risks have also emerged due to rapid adoption of LLMs. Specifically, attackers no longer stop at simple prompt tricks but develop adaptive methods that learn from defenses and evolve over time. This literature review looks into recent studies focusing on such offensive techniques, specifically adaptive and automated attacks meant to probe vulnerabilities in LLMs and their defense gap. The research reveals that several adaptive attack patterns capable of breaking existing defense systems of LLMs. These attacks evolve through reinforcement learning, leveraging contextual prompts, and targeting the model's logic and the surrounding systems. Different safeguard techniques, such as filtering or trust based controls, have been proposed by researchers but the majority of them remain limited in considering evolving threats. The increasing gap between adaptive attacks and static defenses highlights an urgent need to develop more resilient protection strategies.
Keywords—Large Language Models (LLMs), Adaptive Attacks, Prompt Injection, Reinforcement Learning, Model Security, Adversarial Vulnerabilities.
I. INTRODUCTION
Large Language Models are now widely used in most of the day-to-day applications we use, from GPT to Claude, to Llama, integrated in different tools for communication like WhatsApp and Instagram, software development, and making decisions. Their impressive progress in understanding and generating human like text have also raised new security issues. Currently being integrated into external systems via APIs and autonomous agents, they have also become potential targets for attackers.
While there are studies, mainly focused on defensive techniques and bias mitigation, the recent studies show the importance in understanding the Offensive side of LLM security. The attackers are no longer restricted to simple prompt injections or leaks, instead, they go for adaptive methods that learn over time from the system responses to surpass the safety mechanisms. For instance, reinforcement learning-driven agents, contextual multi-turn attacks, and data manipulation techniques target both model logic as well as deployment infrastructure.
Understanding how active attacks work is crucial for defence design. In general, offensive strategies emphasises the recurring nature of vulnerabilities, which explains why defences fail when facing dynamic learning-based threats. This literature review covers recent research into active perspectives with a particular focus on how adaptive, automated, and transfer attacks test the stability and trustworthiness of modern LLMs and also covers about the how weak the defensive systems are against the adaptive strategy and gaps to be worked.
II. ANALYSIS OF OFFENSIVE SECURITY TRENDS AND ATTACK STRATEGIES IN LARGE LANGUAGE MODELS
A. Foundational Security Landscape and Taxonomy
Security concerns for LLMs have grown rapidly fast, with these systems moving from research labs to daily usage applications. Early studies found that, unlike standard machine learning models, LLMs are more prone to attack due to their open-ended text interfaces and dependence on huge, complex, unstructured datasets. According to OWSAP and a survey of published studies, it is reported that inference-time attacks, such as prompt injection and jail breaks, are top documented LLM vulnerabilities [1]. The threats are grouped into categories ranging from data poisoning to model inversion and side-channel leakage, pointing out how each targets a different phase of the model lifecycle. It is also important to note that privacy leakage and data exposure are among the most common recurring risks in open-weight and proprietary systems.
The broader taxonomy explains security issues from an engineering point of view [6]. The study observed that poor API governance, improper access controls, and badly configured runtime environments can lead to misuse of deployed models in production. The study also suggested defence in depth, that combines adversarial training and realtime continuous monitoring with dynamic trust scoring. These two works provide a baseline on where and how attacks occur. Therefore, it is evident that the security of LLMs alone cannot be confined to model architectures but will have to span data pipelines, interaction layers, and operational infrastructures.
B. Prompt Injection and Indirect Attacks
The Prompt injection has quickly become one of the most easy and noticeable technique people use to exploit LLMs. In simple terms, it happens when someone inserts hidden or malicious instructions into what looks like a normal input or external piece of data. The goal is to manipulate how the model behaves or maybe to make it leak private information, ignore safety rules, reveal system prompt or respond in unintended way. There are two types Direct and Indirect Prompt injection. Roughly, one-third of all documented LLM security issues involve some form of prompt manipulation [1]. It is found that once attackers start adjusting their tactics based on how the system reacts, many of today’s defences fall apart [2]. These experiments showed that even simple filters or rulebased protections can be surpassed with a bit of patience and iteration. Interestingly, the models sometimes give away too much through subtle feedback or clues that attackers can then use to fine-tune their next move.
Researchers have also investigated different variations of these manipulations. One of the most common attacks is the jailbreak attack. In this type of attack, the user designs a prompt to make the model ignore its own rules or system instructions. It is framed as role-play situations or casual


conversations that slowly manipulate the model into producing restricted content. Another popular tactic involves character substitutions or encoding, basically swapping sensitive terms with symbols, Unicode lookalikes, or coded text to slip past keyword filters. Jailbreaks and these obfuscation tactics accounts for big portion of real-world exploits. They are easy to execute but hard to stop using static defence [1].
More complex attacks are evolving currently, using reinforcement learning, multi-turn and contextual strategies like RL-Agent and Chain-Of-Attack (CoA). That’s why recent work emphasizes the need for adaptive defences that can evolve over time through continuous context checks, adversarial retraining, and real-time monitoring that adapts as the attackers do.
C. Automated, Reinforcement, and Semantic-Driven Adaptive Attacks
Many prompt-based attacks so for rely on a good amount of trial-and-error method, but recent studies suggests that things are shifting toward something more advanced. Attackers are using automation and adaptive learning to scale their reach and sharpen their tactics. In fact, in the survey it is mentioned that fewer than ten percent of current defense papers even consider threats from automated or learningbased systems, even though those are quickly becoming the next big threat [1]. The most concerning issue is that the adaptive attacks learn from their mistakes to craft a new prompt to attack the target model.
A key example is the Reinforcement Learning–Driven LLM Agent for Automated Attacks on LLMs [3], which presents a framework called RLTA (Reinforcement Learning Targeted Attack) where an RL agent is trained in a way that automatically probes a target model to discover and exploit its weaknesses. Think of it as an attacker that teaches itself. The RL-agent keeps probing a target model, collecting small signals about what works and what doesn’t. Every success or failure becomes a lesson, a reinforcement signal or score is assigned as penalty that helps it fine-tune its attack policy. After enough learnings, it starts generating entirely new and better prompts that surpass restrictions. This transition from simple manually written prompt to self-improving agents is a significant step in how LLM attacks are evolving.
One more adaptive approach called Semantic-Driven Contextual Multi-Turn Attacker (CoA) described in [4]. Instead of using explicit reward feedback, it works on choosing strategy based on the calculated semantic coherence using attack prompt, model response and conversation history. Depending on the coherence value the strategy is chosen whether the attack chain should proceed to next turn or stay and regenerate the current turn or back propagate to previous turn. It’s not brute force. Using semantic coherence result as its feedback loop, the CoA shows that attackers can mimic the reasoning style of the model itself.
Put together, these two studies reveal new path toward adaptive automation. One such is reinforcement-Learning and the other is contextual reasoning. At their core, both works on the same idea that is learning and adapting in real time with the evolving victim’s response. [1], [6] The
adaptive methods are the fastest-growing category of LLM attacks, but current defenses remain insufficient in addressing the risks of advanced optimization based attacks and there is also a concern about how runtime protections rarely evolve automatically, leaving systems open to self-learning adversaries. The combined use of reinforcement learning and semantic reasoning in automated attacks creates a high risk in LLM security. Using these techniques attacks can improve faster than the defenses meant to stop them.
D. Transferable and Universal Adversarial Attacks on Aligned LLMs
A growing focus in offensive LLM research is on transferability, the ability of one attack to work across multiple aligned models. Instead of tailoring prompts for each system, attackers can design inputs that bypass defenses in different architectures, datasets, or platforms. This means a single, well-crafted attack can be reused against several models without starting from scratch which is a big threat in model security and increase the attack speed.
A good example comes from Universal and Transferable Adversarial Attacks on Aligned LLMs [5]. The researchers behind that study managed to generate a universal and transferable adversarial suffix using Greedy Coordinate Gradient (GCG) approach, where models gradients and embeddings are known. The interesting part is sometimes even a smaller changes like minor shifts in word meaning or structure results changes in the token or embedding level that were enough to cause misclassifications or weird, unintended outputs. The adaptive GCG attacks show high success rate against open-source LLMs like Vicuna and LLaMA-2, as well as proprietary, black-box models such as ChatGPT, GPT-4, Bard, and Claude.
For an instance, [5] running against a suite of benchmark objectionable behaviors, it was found that the attack was able to generate 99 (out of 100) harmful behaviors in Vicuna, and generate 88 (out of 100) exact matches with a target (potential harmful) string in its output and prompts achieve up to 84% success rates at attacking GPT-3.5 and GPT-4, and 66% for PaLM-2. While success rate is lower (2.1%) in Claude, still the attack managed to trigger the unintended response.
