III. RESEARCH GAPS AND FUTURE WORK
While Table I highlights methodological constraints in current offensive research, at the same time it also exposes deeper defensive blind spots. This analysis shows that offensive techniques are increasingly adaptive, automated, and transferable. The following subsections discuss where current practices falls short and outline practical directions to move defenses toward the same principle of adaptation.
A. Identified Research Gaps
The current landscape shows a clear pattern that safeguards are failing to keep pace with adaptive adversaries. Most defences remain static, fixed prompt filters, one-off finetuning, and reactive moderation. [1] Rule-based and retraining approaches work against known exploits but falter when attackers evolve and [6] from a systems perspective, noting that existing runtime controls are largely reactive and slow to adapt. safeguards are failing to keep pace with adaptive adversaries
First, there is no broadly accepted adaptive defence loop. Offense now iterates with reinforcement and semantic planning but defence largely do not. Second, evaluation is fragmented. Many studies report single-model or single-turn results, with limited testing of cross-model transfer or multiturn resilience. Third problem is context isolation which is weak. Indirect and chain-of-attack prompts exploit long conversation history and tool outputs only few systems enforce strict provenance or compartmentalize memory across tasks. Fourth, operational visibility is limited. Teams often lack continuous telemetry and drift signals that would surface evolving misuse not just known bad strings. Finally, disclosure and benchmarking are inconsistent. Without shared red-team traces and reproducible test suites, robustness claims are difficult to compare across deployments.
B. Future Work
The reviewed papers focused on various attack techniques and how they evolved over the time and defence limitations. The adaptive attacks are real threat to the LLMs which can cause adversarial effects if it gets in to the hands of bad actor. So, it is high to build the robust defence system that adapts to the attack strategy which is adaptive defence [6]. Instead of having multiple individual static and filtering rules we can build a adaptive defence framework which is a combination of multiple defence techniques. As per the research attack rate is lesser when multiple defences are combined. We can also train the LLMs to adopt adversarial patterns that evolve with newly observed attack instead of fixed prompt sets at inference time, use runtime monitors that score context risk source origin, tool-call and data-path sensitivity, and abrupt dialogue-state shifts rather than scanning for keywords alone.
For agent and API settings, enforce a technique to verify and transform external content before it enters the prompt window, attach taint labels (metadata that marks untrusted tokens and origin) so downstream calls can treat them cautiously. Using these multi-layered, adaptive strategies, transferable attacks can also be prevented. A strict evaluation is also needed to test the efficiency of the defence mechanisms. Finally, a continuous red teaming automated attacks gives defenders a chance to learn under the same feedback dynamics attackers already exploit.
IV. CONCLUSION
Large Language Models (LLMs) are now a core part of everyday computing. The research reviewed here shows that their exposure to adaptive and automated attacks is growing faster than most defenses can adjust. Over the years, these threats have moved from simple prompt injections to multiturn manipulation, reinforcement-based exploits, and transferable attacks that affect across different models. Attackers continue to learn and evolve, while many defenses still rely on static or narrowly tested methods without good benchmarks. To keep pace, security work needs to focus on adaptive, self-learning protection systems, supported by open benchmarks and real-time tracking. In the end, studying about offensive security and working on attacking strategy is important as it helps to create a robust defense mechanism.
